\begin{abstract}
%
Narrow-band images of the core of the extraordinary poly-polar planetary
nebula KjPn 8 have been obtained with the WFPC2 camera on board the Hubble 
Space Telescope. Spasmodic bipolar ejections, in changing directions have
occurred over thousands of years to create KjPn 8. The central star is finally
revealed in these observations and its compact nebular core is resolved into
a remarkably young $\approx$ 500 years old, elliptical ionized ring. The 
highest speed bipolar outflows are perpendicular to this central ring which
is identified as the latest event in the creation of this nebula. The 
formation history of KjPn 8 has involved two distinct planetary nebula-like
events, probably originating from a binary core evolution with components of
similar mass.
%
\end{abstract}


